Honestly feel like these well-meaning but unhelpful attempts to be inclusive just add more fuel to the fire. It IS possible to be inclusive AND accurate AND acknowledge medical misogyny (& transphobia) all at once, without reducing anyone to their anatomy.

The only inclusive language I‚Äôve EVER seen actual trans people advocating for is the gender additive approach (i.e. women/men and [relevant descriptor]), which actually is far more inclusive and allows you to be both accurate & specific about the health issue(s) you‚Äôre describing

Plenty of trans women, and all post-menopausal women, have vaginas but don‚Äôt menstruate. People on hormonal contraception typically have vaginas but don‚Äôt menstruate, because a withdrawal bleed is not menstruation.

But we also, for the sake of our appalling collective health literacy, need to be accurate and specific about who & what we‚Äôre talking about. If we‚Äôre talking about menstruation, vaginas are NOT even the relevant feature, which you‚Äôd expect @TheLancet to know.

ME is a great (non-vagina related) example of a condition that has been neglected BECAUSE it primarily affects women. That doesn‚Äôt men aren‚Äôt also affected, in different & similar ways, by the result of that neglect & the sexist stigma that still surrounds it. Both can be true.

We can talk about the fact that women‚Äôs health (which isn‚Äôt just obs&gynae, by the way) has been systematically neglected because of sexism and medical misogyny while acknowledging that this also has an impact on people who are not women.

There is absolutely a conversation to be had about trans inclusive language (including trans/NB people who were assigned male at birth, as well as those AFAB) but ‚Äúbodies with vaginas‚Äù is not the one, and doesn‚Äôt do women, trans men or AFAB non-binary people any favours. https://t.co/AEnHL70YaB
